definition.value: An oligoglycosylceramide in which the oligoglycosyl component is derived from the cyclic form of a disaccharide (or derivative).
The ammonium ion formed from 4-amino-5-aminomethyl-2-methylpyrimidine by protonation of the primary amino group; principle microspecies at pH 7.3.
Dianion of UDP-4-amino-UDP-2,4-diacetamido-2,4,6-trideoxy-beta-L-altrose arising from deprotonation of the diphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
The penicilloate(2-) species that is the dianion formed from benzylpenicilloic acid by deprotonation of both carboxy groups. It is the major microspecies present at pH 7.3.

A glycosylphosphatidylinositol that can be attached to the C-terminal amino acid of a mature protein during posttranslational modification.  The phosphatidylinositol group is linked through a carbohydrate-containing linker (glucosamine and mannose glycosidically bound to the inositol residue) and via an ethanolamine phosphate bridge to the C-terminal amino acid, while the two fatty acids within the hydrophobic phosphatidylinositol group anchor the protein to the cell membrane.
A UDP-amino sugar having 4-amino-4,6-dideoxy-L-N-acetyl-beta-L-altrosamine as the amino sugar component.
Pyranose form of altrose in beta-L configuration
A UDP-amino sugar having 2,4-diacetamido-2,4,6-trideoxy-beta-L-altrose as the amino sugar component.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from an alditol.
An alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a glycosyl alditol.
A glycosyl alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a galactosylglycerol.
A glycosyl alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a glucosylglycerol.
A glycosyl alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a glycosyl glycerol.
A glycosylglycerol derivative that is formally obtained from a digalactosylglycerol.
An alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a heptitol.

A diastereoisomeric mixture of approximately equal amounts of all four possible stereoisomers ((R,S)-labetolol, (S,R)-labetolol, (S,S)-labetalol and (R,R)-labetalol). It is an adrenergic antagonist used to treat high blood pressure.
An alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a hexitol.
A hexitol derivative that is formally obtained from a 2-deoxyhexitol.
A hexitol derivative that is formally obtained from a galactitol.
A hexitol derivative that is formally obtained from a glucitol.
An alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a pentitol.
An alditol derivative that is formally obtained from a tetritol.
A carbohydrate derivative that is formally obtained from a carbohydrate acid.
A carbohydrate acid derivative that is formally obtained from an aldaric acid.
An aldaric acid derivative that is formally obtained from a hexaric acid.
An aldaric acid derivative that is formally obtained from a pentaric acid.
An aldaric acid derivative that is formally obtained from a tetraric acid.
A carbohydrate acid derivative that is formally obtained from an aldonic acid.
An aldonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from a hexonic acid.

A carbobicyclic compound and sesquiterpene that is 1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8-octahydroazulene which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 1 and 4 and by a (prop-1-en-2-yl group at position 7 (the 1S,4S,7R enantiomer).
A carbotricyclic sesquiterpene obtained from several natural sources, including Australian Tea Tree oil (Melaleuca alternifolia.)
An isomer of selinene where the double bond in the octahydronaphthalene ring system is endocyclic with (2R,4aR,8aS)-configuration. It has been isolated from termites.
A tertiary alcohol resulting from the formal addition of water to the double bond of alpha-cubebene.

A carbobicyclic compound and sesquiterpene that is 1,2,3,3a,4,5,6,7-octahydroazulene which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 3 and 8 and by a (prop-1-en-2-yl group at position 5 (the 3S,3aS,5R enantiomer).

A member of the class of ureas that is 1-tert-butylurea in which one of the hydrogens attached to N(3) is substituted by a pyrido[2,3-d]pyrimidin-7-yl group, which is itself substituted at positions 2 and 6 by a 4-(diethylamino)butyl]amino group and a 3,5-dimethoxyphenyl group, respectively. It is a FGF/VEGF receptor tyrosine kinase inhibitor.

An oxindole that is 3-methyleneoxindole in which one of the hydrogens of the methylene group is substituted by a 3-(2-carboxyethyl)-4-methyl-1H-pyrrol-2-yl group. It is an ATP-competitive inhibitor of the tyrosine kinase activity of fibroblast growth factor receptor 1.

A member of the class of benzamides that is the carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-[(4-methylpiperazin-1-yl)methyl]benzoic acid with the primary amino group of 4-methyl-N(3)-[4-(pyridin-3-yl)-1,3-thiazol-2-yl]benzene-1,3-diamine. It is a highly selective oral tyrosine kinase inhibitor.

A member of the class of phenylureas that is urea in which a hydrogen attached to one of the nitrogens is replaced by a 2,6-dichloro-3,5-dimethoxyphenyl group, while the hydrogens attached to the other nitrogen are replaced by a methyl group and a 6-{[4-(4-ethylpiperazin-1-yl)phenyl]amino}pyrimidin-4-yl group. It is a potent and selective fibroblast growth factor receptor inhibitor.
An organic heterooctacyclic compound that is the N-benzoyl derivative of staurosporine.

A member of the class of  benzamides  that is a carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-(cis-3,5-dimethylpiperazin-1-yl)benzoic acid with the amino substituent of 5-[2-(3,5-dimethoxyphenyl)ethyl]-1H-pyrazol-3-amine. It is an inhibitor of the fibroblast growth factor receptor (FGFR).
An aldonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from a pentonic acid.
An aldonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from a tetronic acid.
An aldonic acid derivative that is formally obtained from a trionic acid.
An antagonist at the fibroblast growth factor receptor.
An acyl-CoA(4-) oxoanion arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate OH groups of 2-(1,2-epoxy-1,2-dihydrophenyl)acetyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.

A tetracyclic triterpenoid that is perhydrochrysene which is substituted by methyl groups at positions 1, 4bbeta, 6aalpha, 8beta, 10abeta and 12a positions, by a 4-methylpent-3-enyl group at the 8alpha position, and with an oxo group at position 2.
